		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: M-Tee's Graphics Projects (Isolation Spoilers)</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />#$20 and #$30 are the exact same voltage, and so are fully identical whites.<br /><br />I personally like using #$20 just because it's a smaller number.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Thu Jul 14, 2016 7:18 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: M-Tee's Graphics Projects (Isolation Spoilers)</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The difference between $20 and $30 can be seen mostly during a fade out using the common &quot;subtract $10 each step and crush negatives to $0F&quot; method. $20 fades with the rest of the colors; $30 stays bright longer.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


